    q: "Is Nicaraguan coffee usually washed or natural?",
    a: "Historically, Nicaragua has been a washed-coffee country. The infrastructure, climate, and tradition in the major specialty regions (Matagalpa, Jinotega, Nueva Segovia) all developed around wet milling, which produces the clean, balanced cups most associated with Central American specialty. Naturals and anaerobic lots are a recent addition to the Nicaraguan specialty market, driven by global demand for fruit-forward cups rather than by local tradition. The current breakdown is roughly 80-85% washed at the specialty grade, with naturals, honey, and anaerobic lots making up the remainder."
  },
