    q: "What is wet-hulled processing, and is it used in Nicaragua?",
    a: "Wet-hulled processing (Giling Basah) is a method associated almost exclusively with Indonesian Sumatra coffees. The parchment layer is removed from the bean while it still contains significant moisture (unlike in fully washed or natural coffees, where the parchment comes off after the bean is mostly dry). Wet-hulling produces the distinctive earthy, full-bodied, low-acid cup that Sumatran coffees are known for. It is not used in Nicaraguan specialty production. Nicaragua's dominant method is fully washed (wet-processed), where parchment stays on the bean through the entire drying phase and is removed at dry milling before export."
  },
  {
    q: "Does processing or origin matter more for the cup?",
    a: "Both matter, and they interact. Origin (terroir, altitude, soil, variety) sets the ceiling of what a coffee can express; processing determines how much of that ceiling you actually reach and in what direction. A well-processed coffee from mediocre terroir can cup higher than a poorly processed coffee from exceptional terroir. In practice, the combination is what matters: exceptional origin plus disciplined processing produces the best cups. El Quetzal's anaerobic Java is a good example. The Java varietal grown in Matagalpa at 1,200+ MASL provides excellent terroir. The anaerobic processing in sealed fermentation tanks adds another layer that takes the same origin material to 87 points, one point above the washed version of the same cherry."
  },
  {
    q: "Why does the same variety taste different depending on processing?",
    a: "Processing changes which flavor compounds reach the final bean. In washed processing, the mucilage (the sugary fruit layer around the bean) is removed quickly, leaving the bean's inherent varietal character to express through fermentation. The cup reads clean and terroir-forward. In anaerobic processing, the cherry or depulped bean ferments in an oxygen-deprived environment for an extended period, producing different microbial metabolic byproducts that deposit different flavor compounds in the bean. A washed Java at El Quetzal reads jasmine, milk chocolate, and tea-like balance. The same Java variety processed anaerobically reads dark cherry, raisin, and chocolate. Same genetics, same farm, different processing: dramatically different cups."
  },
  {
    q: "What does on-farm milling mean for cup quality?",
    a: "On-farm milling means the farm processes its own cherry rather than selling fresh cherry to a centralized cooperative mill or wet mill. The key quality advantage is timing: cherry-to-tank in hours rather than days. Fresh cherry that sits in a bag or transport vehicle before processing begins to ferment unevenly, introducing off-flavors that no amount of careful downstream processing can remove. When the mill is on the farm, the cherry moves from the tree to the fermentation tank the same day it is picked. El Quetzal's Beneficio San Miguel is an on-farm mill, which is a meaningful quality driver for the lot consistency the farm produces."
  },
  {
    q: "What is anaerobic fermentation and how is it different from standard washed processing?",
    a: "Standard washed processing ferments the depulped coffee in open tanks or channels where oxygen is present. The aerobic microbial environment breaks down the remaining mucilage and produces the compounds that define the washed cup profile. Anaerobic fermentation seals the coffee in oxygen-deprived tanks, suppressing aerobic bacteria and creating a different microbial ecosystem dominated by anaerobic organisms. This different environment produces different metabolic byproducts (including lactic and acetic acids and various flavor esters) that deposit distinct flavor compounds in the bean, shifting the cup toward dried fruit, deeper chocolate, and sometimes wine-like complexity. The process requires tight control over tank sealing, temperature, and fermentation duration; done poorly, it produces off-flavors; done well, it can add a full cup-score point above the same coffee processed conventionally."
