<p class="body">Nicaragua's specialty processing story begins at the mill, not the tree. The two farms that produce identical cherry from the same variety at the same altitude can produce dramatically different cups depending on what happens between picking and export. The most important processing variable is not whether a farm chooses washed or natural: it is whether the farm controls its own processing infrastructure or sells cherry to a centralized mill with different incentive structures and timing constraints.</p>

<p class="body">El Quetzal's Beneficio San Miguel is the case study this guide uses throughout. The on-farm wet mill at Finca El Quetzal in Matagalpa processes all of the farm's cherry in-house, from the picking bags through fermentation tanks, washing channels, and raised-bed drying to export preparation. The result is a supply chain where processing discipline is entirely within the farm's control. <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-washed-java-green-coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">El Quetzal's washed Java</a> and <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-anaerobic-java-green-coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">anaerobic Java</a> are the direct outputs of that infrastructure. This guide explains what each method does, why it matters, and how to choose between El Quetzal's processing options when sourcing.</p>

